'''Johann''' "'''Hans'''" '''Hölzel''' ({{IPA|de|ˈjoːhan hans ˈhœltsl̩|lang}}; 19 February 1957 – 6 February 1998), better known by his stage name '''Falco''' (from [[Falko Weißpflog]]), was an Austrian musician. He had several international hits, including "[[Der Kommissar (song)|Der Kommissar]]" (1981), "[[Rock Me Amadeus]]", which reached number 18 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], "[[Vienna Calling]]", "[[Jeanny (song)|Jeanny]]", "[[The Sound of Musik]]", "[[Coming Home (Jeanny Part II, One Year Later)]]", and posthumously released "[[Out of the Dark (song)|Out of the Dark]]".

"Rock Me Amadeus" reached No.&nbsp;1 on the [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' charts]] in 1986, making Falco the only artist in history to score a number-one hit with a German-language song in the United States.{{efn|1=[[Bert Kaempfert]] also reached No. 1 in January 1961 but with the instrumental "[[Wonderland by Night]]"}}

According to his estate, he has sold 20 million albums and 40 million singles, making him the best-selling Austrian singer of all time. Falco died in a [[traffic collision]] at the age of 40 in 1998.
